    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2172673408" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2172673408" />
    <a title="Tsung" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung"><img alt="Tsung" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298808605p2/4992851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2172673408?book_show_action=true">Mar 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tsung" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tsung" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung">Tsung</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2172673408" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3363765501296199266">This is a story about fictional Arab communities getting wash away in the wave of colonialism. It is a tells about the exploitative, capitalist Americans and the impotence and complicity of local government, but the locals are also to blame for getting seduced by the prospect of wealth and modernization. Wadi Al-Uyoun was an oasis in the desert, a source of pride, history and culture for the local people. It was sitting on top of an oil resource, something that would change their lives forever. </span>
  <span id="freeText3363765501296199266" style="display:none">This is a story about fictional Arab communities getting wash away in the wave of colonialism. It is a tells about the exploitative, capitalist Americans and the impotence and complicity of local government, but the locals are also to blame for getting seduced by the prospect of wealth and modernization. Wadi Al-Uyoun was an oasis in the desert, a source of pride, history and culture for the local people. It was sitting on top of an oil resource, something that would change their lives forever. It would be superseded by the settlement of Harran. The story tells about the people of these two places and how their society is irrevocably disrupted. <br /><br />The Americans are presented as opportunistic, supercilious, hedonistic bullies, but ironically they are never involved directly in any confrontation. They are passive-aggressive and sow the seeds of disharmony among the local people. The naive locals whole heartedly embrace the invaders, not understanding the consequences of their actions; the erosion of their culture, the mistrust and disunity amongst themselves.<br /><br />There is no main protagonist or a main storyline but the novel is a series of narratives of different characters. Miteb realizes the dangers early on but gives up the fight and disappears. Despite not being physically present, he becomes a local mythical hero, the people’s champion of sorts. There are segments on a number of different men who struggle to survive and to keep the community together. The local government is represented by the emir, who is clueless, incompetent and more interested in what he can gain from the Americans. There are also the middlemen who reckon that they can please everybody but are hated by all.<br /><br />It seems to be a cautionary sociopolitical commentary. It has shades of “War with the Newts” and “Things Fall Apart”. Overall, a fair read. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3363765501296199266" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


