    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2756386410" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2756386410" />
    <a title="Clif" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1241339-clif"><img alt="Clif" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509420212p2/1241339.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2756386410?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clif" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clif" href="/user/show/1241339-clif">Clif</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1241339-clif?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2756386410" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3362827288222840564">Is mankind suited to modernity? By modernity I mean the kind of life we now cannot escape where things change all the time, facts are scientific and we are, above all, consumers. We know we like the goodies and boredom is a thing of the past but is this life truly satisfying to the heart?<br/><br/>I&apos;d love to hear a formal debate about this. For the side arguing the negative, a rich source of material could be found in a book about Native-American life, <i>Hanta Yo</i>, the classic of rural life in 19th century </span>
  <span id="freeText3362827288222840564" style="display:none">Is mankind suited to modernity? By modernity I mean the kind of life we now cannot escape where things change all the time, facts are scientific and we are, above all, consumers. We know we like the goodies and boredom is a thing of the past but is this life truly satisfying to the heart?<br /><br />I'd love to hear a formal debate about this. For the side arguing the negative, a rich source of material could be found in a book about Native-American life, <i>Hanta Yo</i>, the classic of rural life in 19th century Colombia, <i>One Hundred Years of Solitude</i> and this book which was written in Arabic but has been translated to English by Peter Theroux.<br /><br />We are introduced to an oasis in the desert where friendly people greet weary travelers in caravans that stop for water and trade. Everyone has a place in this small society and religion frames everything. No conversation goes without aphorisms; small bits of wisdom held up as guides to live by. Nothing is planned without the admission that god must be willing for it to succeed. Life is secure and people know who they are.<br /><br />Within this society, only the very few who have traveled have seen any large body of water. The things so familiar to us such as radios and telephones are unknown as is the very basis of modern life, electricity, though it is around 1930.<br /><br />The theme that runs throughout the book is the coming of the Americans who are eager to exploit the oil beneath the sands. Characteristic of the age of development of resources by the West, the locals are used for labor but are otherwise oddities with a strange language and habits that mystify, amuse and, for a few, fascinate those whose sole reason for coming is to make money and leave. Arrangements are always made over the heads of the people directly affected, something that continues today. The locals must defer to what some notable in another place has decided on with foreigners, to his undoubted benefit.<br /><br />This is a recipe at least for discomfort and disorientation if not complete disaster. The latter occurs to the oasis which is completely destroyed to be replaced by drilling rigs and an American settlement that uses the cool, clear water primarily for oil extraction (this is no spoiler as what I have described is only the opening of the book). This physical disruption is symbolic of the social disruption that extends over a wide area as the wants and needs of the newcomers redirect the lives of everyone and leave the natives strangers to a new environment that quickly alters the one countless generations have known so intimately.<br /><br />Filled with vivid characters that show the range of reaction to the assault, this book reminds me that the loss of deep social connection is a price that has been paid across the world as one ancient way of life after another has come into contact with modernity and been at least partially if not completely dissolved.<br /><br />Perhaps a good word to use in order to characterize this is business. In the old society, everyone had business with many others every day. This involved exchange of goods, helping to get one task or another done, hunting, worship, celebration and the simple satisfactions of knowing each other so well that each could freely chastise or compliment another in line with a common sense of what was right and wrong.<br /><br />The Americans in <i>Cities of Salt</i> are not cruel and try to accommodate the natives in their clueless way, but they are all business in the modern sense of wanting to get something done to make money. They are either intent on the work or intent on partying, seeming shallow, even crazy, to people with no understanding of deadlines and the bottom line.<br /><br />There are exceptions, the Americans who simply can't get enough of the ethnic color they see in the Arabs. Humor runs throughout the book and one of the funniest parts concerns the Americans who follow the Arabs around asking a million questions about their daily lives, taking pictures and filling notebooks with writing. Yet this intense curiosity fails to break the barrier. There is no American who appreciates the Arabs for themselves or who feels comfortable with them as fellow human beings.<br /><br />If you want excitement and adventure, you will find this a slow read. If you enjoy people and personalities then this book is for you as you get pulled into the account of a baker who goes in for pornography, the emir who is obsessed with the telescope and radio he receives as presents and the feuding truck drivers that struggle to make a living in competition only to end up the best of friends. I have rarely felt so much in the shoes of another as when Abdulrahman Munif describes the reaction of people who see the ocean for the first time, feeling both fear and astonishment that ships, such huge things, can sit out there on top of the water!<br /><br />The feeling you will develop for the natives is a tribute to Munif's writing skill. Here is a short example that touched me as two people long absent arrive home in a caravan...<br /><br />"As soon as the caravan arrived the people swarmed around it. Much sooner than they thought, at the first looks they exchanged with people, the two felt enveloped in an atmosphere of home and friends. The people crowded around them as if they had been away only on a short trip. Time had left its marks on all their faces, but these marks were dissolved by the emotions underneath, and these emotions revealed the inner strength which eliminated time and distance, returning their features to their original loveliness."<br /><br />When I finished the 630 pages of this book book, I couldn't help wondering: we have so much stuff now, but what have we done to ourselves?</span>
  <a data-text-id="3362827288222840564" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

