    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2005297557" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2005297557" />
    <a title="Brian Cubbage" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10825808-brian-cubbage"><img alt="Brian Cubbage" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451743857p2/10825808.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2005297557?book_show_action=true">Nov 26, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian Cubbage" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian Cubbage" href="/user/show/10825808-brian-cubbage">Brian Cubbage</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2005297557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18346337353079031288"><i>Cities of Salt</i> is a sprawling, fascinating read that defies most of our customary expectations of how a novel is supposed to behave. The idea is pretty straightforward: chronicle the impact that the discovery of oil, and the advent of American oil companies, has on rural towns in an unnamed Persian Gulf state. <br/><br/>The execution, however, is anything but straightforward. There is no one who could plausibly be thought of as the &quot;protagonist.&quot; Multiple individuals arise in the course of the story as ca</span>
  <span id="freeText18346337353079031288" style="display:none"><i>Cities of Salt</i> is a sprawling, fascinating read that defies most of our customary expectations of how a novel is supposed to behave. The idea is pretty straightforward: chronicle the impact that the discovery of oil, and the advent of American oil companies, has on rural towns in an unnamed Persian Gulf state. <br /><br />The execution, however, is anything but straightforward. There is no one who could plausibly be thought of as the "protagonist." Multiple individuals arise in the course of the story as candidates for such a title, only to disappear, die, or be moved aside as the story focuses instead on another series of events in which those figures do not take part. It also doesn't have a plot in the customary sense of "this happens, then this happens, then because of this other thing a third thing happens." The narrative hangs together, but the overarching narrative principle is less a single plot than a series of incidents that take on metaphorical (and, in the end, very nearly magical) resonances with one another.<br /><br />It is also noteworthy in that the Arab characters living through the impact of the Americans' oil venture are the exclusive focus of the story, yet very little of what they do or fail to do has any direct impact on the ultimate outcome of events. The real drivers of what is happening are the Americans, yet there are perhaps twenty pages (in a novel of 627 pages) in which an American character is named, and even more rarely do they speak. It is almost like a painting or a sculpture in which the foreground image is entirely composed of negative space: the real drivers of events are barely hinted at and gestured towards largely in silence. It is difficult not to see this technique as deliberate, especially as the one character who comes closest to being the thematic bridge spanning the whole work--Miteb al-Hathal--literally rides into the desert in the first 100 pages and only "reappears" as a sort of specter, as a folk hero of resistance to the Americans and a convenient scapegoat for the ruling government who may or may not even still be alive. <br /><br />Only in the final brief chapter does a character pronounce what feels like a definitive verdict: All of the problems of petty corruption and unrest that rock the region and lead to a final semi-climactic uprising are first and foremost caused by the Americans, whose role remains hidden behind their literally gated communities and their desire to keep their hands symbolically clean of anything negative that happens. It's a verdict that, in this reviewer's humble opinion, stands the test of time.<br /><br />I can only hope that more of this work--the first of a trilogy--appears in English at some point in the future.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18346337353079031288" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

