    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3784136809" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3784136809" />
    <a title="Shira Baharin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26759075-shira-baharin"><img alt="Shira Baharin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1387551703p2/26759075.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3784136809?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shira Baharin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shira Baharin" href="/user/show/26759075-shira-baharin">Shira Baharin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3784136809" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer755730813458446866">This is an unconventional reading experience, since the structure emphasises no plot or main characters. Instead the author follows a loose third person narrative of random characters, following the destruction of a village to make way for an oil field, the displacement of its residents, and their subsequent attempts at adapting to a new world, encroaching modernity and Western influences.<br/><br/>The book mainly highlights the disrespect the Americans show towards the same locals that they hire to work </span>
  <span id="freeText755730813458446866" style="display:none">This is an unconventional reading experience, since the structure emphasises no plot or main characters. Instead the author follows a loose third person narrative of random characters, following the destruction of a village to make way for an oil field, the displacement of its residents, and their subsequent attempts at adapting to a new world, encroaching modernity and Western influences.<br /><br />The book mainly highlights the disrespect the Americans show towards the same locals that they hire to work in their plants and construction sites as labour, and how badly the Bedu are treated. The local government seems completely disinterested in the struggles of the people, and the emir seems more keen on getting his hands on the latest technological marvel rather than taking an active role in governing, perhaps the reason this book is considered controversial and banned in Saudi Arabia.<br /><br />It's a long and slow read, but ultimately rewarding as a contemplation of the price that is paid for modernity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="755730813458446866" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


